{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510948"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11665"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11665"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.26,0.39,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4286"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4286"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37149"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1685"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic for infertility. Despite regular and normal intercourse over the last two years, his wife has not conceived. They have been happily married for three years. His wife has a son from a previous marriage. Information is sought from the history that might help reveal an underlying cause for his infertility.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be relevant?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Childhood mumps","Presence of a varicocele","Previous surgery for an ectopic testis","Previous episode of prostatitis","Childhood exposure to asbestos"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopic testes\u003C/strong\u003E, which is rarer than true cryptorchidism, is a congenital condition in which the testes fail to descend into the scrotum. Some 3% - 5% of newborns will have a palpable ectopic testis and in most cases this will descend into the scrotum within the first four months of life. This ectopic testis is most often located in the femoral, penile or perineal region. The ectopic testicle, like the cryptorchid testicle, is capable of testosterone production; however, spermatogenesis is often hindered because of exposure to high body temperature. The most distant the mal-descended testis is from its correct position in the scrotum and the longer that it has been outside the scrotum the more the risk of infertility. Unilateral cryptorchidism will frequently be associated with lower than expected sperm counts and this suggests that cryptorchidism may be associated with inherent defects in both testes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ectopic testicle may create problems if not surgically removed, such as testicular cord torsion, pain or colic signs, neoplastic transformation, or undesired male behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJust under half of all males who get \u003Cstrong\u003Emumps-related orchitis \u003C/strong\u003Enotice some shrinkage of their testicles and an estimated 1 in 10 men experience a drop in their sperm count (the amount of healthy sperm their body can produce). However, this is very rarely large enough to cause infertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA varicocele \u003C/strong\u003Edoes not necessarily cause infertility. An estimated 10% to 20% of men diagnosed with a varicocele experience difficulty fathering a child. Whilst it is a recognised cause of infertility, a varicocele is not the most common cause, but it is perhaps the most correctable cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstatitis \u003C/strong\u003Eitself does not lead to infertility, but there is a significant correlation with influence on sperm parameters - such as sperm count and motility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe strongest evidence for reproductive disease due to \u003Cstrong\u003Easbestos\u003C/strong\u003E is in regard to ovarian cancer. Unfortunately, effects on fertility and the developing fetus are under-studied.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ectopic testes, which is rarer than true cryptorchidism, is a congenital condition in which the testes fail to descend into the scrotum."],"references":["Gadelkareem RA, Shahat AA, Reda A. et al. Ectopic testis: an experience of a tertiary-level urology center at Upper Egypt. Ann Pediatr Surg 2020;16:27. Available at: https://aops.springeropen.com/articles/10.1186/s43159-020-00038-8","Eisenberg ML, Esteves SC, Lamb DJ, et al. Male Infertility. Nat Rev Dis Primers 2023; 9:49"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11665"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37149"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-30T09:28:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-30T09:29:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4286"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51847"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200